properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke from wildfires in northern Alberta is causing poor air quality and reducing visibility in some areas. Some smoke is expected to push into central Alberta today and this alert will be expanded southward if smoke remains near the surface as it moves away from the fires. ### Individuals may experience symptoms such as increased coughing, throat irritation, headaches or shortness of breath. Children, seniors, and those with cardiovascular or lung disease, such as asthma, are especially at risk. People with lung diseases, such as asthma and COPD, can be particularly sensitive to air pollution. They will generally experience more serious health effects at lower levels. Pollution can aggravate their diseases, leading to increased medication use, doctor and emergency room visits, and hospital visits. For more information please visit Alberta Health Services at www.albertahealthservices.ca/news/air.aspx. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Summary:
Description: Thunderstorms tracking over Lake Erie from Michigan have the potential to produce wind gusts to 40 knots along with small hail and frequent lightning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - Wildfire Alert Updated
properties.Summary:
Description: The wildfire 14 km southeast of the Trout Lake Community is still out of control but remains a distance from the community. The public should continue to monitor information regarding this wildfire for their safety. There is heavy smoke from this wildfire in the area and this will cause issues regarding driving visibility, and concerns for people with breathing issues.### The Trout Lake Community is the most southern area of the Peerless Trout First Nation area and these communities are on the south shores of Peerless Lake. Peerless Trout First Nation website is www.ptfn.net and https://www.facebook.com/peerlesstroutfirstnation/ is the Facebook page for this community. Additional Wildfire information is also available at www.wildfire.alberta.ca website. Check https://511.alberta.ca/region/Northern%20Alberta#:Alerts for more information on road conditions.

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke from wildfires in northern Alberta is causing poor air quality and reducing visibility in some areas. In central parts of the province smoke is expected to move back north by Friday morning as the flow shifts to southeasterly. ### Individuals may experience symptoms such as increased coughing, throat irritation, headaches or shortness of breath. Children, seniors, and those with cardiovascular or lung disease, such as asthma, are especially at risk. People with lung diseases, such as asthma and COPD, can be particularly sensitive to air pollution. They will generally experience more serious health effects at lower levels. Pollution can aggravate their diseases, leading to increased medication use, doctor and emergency room visits, and hospital visits. For more information please visit Alberta Health Services at www.albertahealthservices.ca/news/air.aspx. Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2019-05-31T04:23:02-00:00

Description: Due to extremely dry conditions and unstable wildfire activity, the Town of Slave Lake is on an 8 hour Evacuation Alert. This is not an Evacuation Order. ### The Town is not in imminent danger however residents should be prepared to evacuate on short notice. Please ensure your have any medications or prescriptions, drinking water and food and fuel in your vehicle. You may want to bring identification, passports,insurance policies and other important documents. Please consider arrangements for your pets should you be required to leave the community.

Description: Elevated pollution levels are expected or occurring. High levels of air pollution have developed due to smoke from forest fires. Smoke plumes moving over Pikangikum from forest fires east of the community have resulted in deteriorated air quality in the area. Individuals may experience symptoms such as increased coughing, throat irritation, headaches or shortness of breath. Children, seniors and those with cardiovascular or lung disease, such as asthma, are especially at risk. If you, or someone in your care, develop symptoms, reduce or reschedule strenuous outdoors activities where ever possible until the air quality improves. ### Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
